---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import BrandMark from '../components/BrandMark.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<BaseLayout>
  <Header>
    <BrandMark slot="mark" />
  </Header>

  <main>
    <section class="section hero-section">
      <div class="shell surface-dark pad hero-card">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <div class="meta-label">Trust</div>
          <h1 class="page-hero-title">Trust as explicit system structure.</h1>
          <p class="page-copy">
            Aster implements a four-gate authorization model built on ed25519 cryptography.
            No external auth infrastructure. No certificate authority. No OAuth sidecar.
            Trust is operator-defined, credential-scoped, and auditable at every gate.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="trust-rail">
          <span>Gate 0 · Connection</span>
          <span>Gate 1 · Admission</span>
          <span>Gate 2 · Service</span>
          <span>Gate 3 · Method</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="shell surface-light-wrap">
        <div class="surface-light pad">
          <div class="section-head">
            <div>
              <div class="meta-label">Trust model</div>
               <h2 class="page-section-title">Portable trust, operator-shaped.</h2>
            </div>
             <p class="page-copy">
              Every trust decision is concrete and auditable. The root authority signs enrollment
              credentials. Admission is enforced at the QUIC ALPN layer. Capabilities are scoped
              to services and methods. Credentials carry expiry and can be rotated without
              breaking contract or peer identity.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="grid grid-2">
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Root authority</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Offline ed25519 root key</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">The root key is generated offline (<code>generate_root_keypair()</code>) and never needs to be present at runtime. It signs enrollment credentials that carry the root public key, expiry, endpoint scope, and custom attributes.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Admission</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Producer and consumer enrollment</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Producers present signed <code>EnrollmentCredential</code> objects. Consumers use either reusable policy credentials or single-use one-time-token nonces (<code>ConsumerEnrollmentCredential</code>). The <code>MeshEndpointHook</code> enforces admission at the QUIC ALPN layer.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Four-gate model</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Connection, admission, service, method</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Gate 0 validates the QUIC connection. Gate 1 checks enrollment credentials with signature and expiry verification. Gate 2 authorizes service-level access. Gate 3 applies method-level capability constraints. Each gate can be independently configured.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Dev mode</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Local transport bypasses trust</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">When using <code>LocalTransport</code> for development, <code>CallContext.peer</code> is <code>None</code> and all gates pass. The same service code enforces full authorization in production without changes. Credential rotation and revocation are normal operational behaviour.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="shell surface-dark pad">
        <div class="section-head dark">
          <div>
            <div class="meta-label">Credential lifecycle</div>
             <h2 class="page-section-title">Signed, scoped, expiring, rotatable.</h2>
          </div>
           <p class="page-copy">
            Every credential is an ed25519-signed object with explicit expiry, endpoint scope, and
            custom attributes. Nonce stores prevent replay. The canonical signing format is deterministic
            JSON. Keys, leases, and authority can rotate without breaking contract identity or peer
            relationships. This is not decentralisation as a vibe. It is an auditable trust model
            for systems operating across mixed environments.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .pad { padding: 26px; }
  .hero-section { padding-top: 24px; }
  .hero-card, .section-head { display: grid; gap: 18px; }
  .hero-card { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.25fr) 240px; align-items: end; }
  .hero-copy h1 { max-width: 11ch; }
  .hero-copy p { color: var(--mist); }
  .section-head { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.1fr) minmax(280px, 0.9fr); margin-bottom: 22px; align-items: end; }
  .section-head p { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .section-head.dark h2 { color: var(--cloud-strong); }
  .section-head.dark p { color: var(--mist); }
  .trust-rail { display: grid; gap: 10px; }
  .trust-rail span { border-radius: 999px; padding: 10px 12px; border: 1px solid rgba(230,192,107,0.22); background: rgba(230,192,107,0.08); color: var(--cloud-strong); font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: .08em; text-transform: uppercase; }
  .grid { display: grid; gap: 16px; }
  .grid-2 { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr)); }
  .card { border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 18px; }
  .light-card { border: 1px solid rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72); }
  .meta-label { margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.2; letter-spacing: 0.12em; text-transform: uppercase; }
  .card h3 { color: var(--ink); }
  .card p { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  @media (max-width: 960px) {
    .hero-card, .section-head, .grid-2 { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .pad { padding: 22px; }
  }
</style>
